<!-- Q1 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Euler-Cauchy Equation</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The Euler–Cauchy equation \(x^2y''+3xy'+y=0\) has solutions of the form \(y=x^m\). Substituting gives the indicial equation:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(m^2+2m+1=0\)</strong></p><p>Substituting \(y=x^m\): \(y'=mx^{m-1}\), \(y''=m(m-1)x^{m-2}\). So \(x^2\cdot m(m-1)x^{m-2}+3x\cdot mx^{m-1}+x^m=x^m[m(m-1)+3m+1]=x^m[m^2+2m+1]=0\). Indicial equation: \((m+1)^2=0\Rightarrow m=-1\) (repeated). Solution: \(y=(c_1+c_2\ln x)x^{-1}\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m^2+3m+1=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m^2+2m+1=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m^2-m+1=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(m^2+4m+3=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q2 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Solution of x^2y'' - 2y = 0</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The general solution of \(x^2y''-2y=0\) for \(x>0\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(y=c_1x^2+c_2x^{-1}\)</strong></p><p>Indicial equation: \(m(m-1)-2=0\Rightarrow m^2-m-2=(m-2)(m+1)=0\Rightarrow m=2,-1\). Two distinct roots give independent solutions \(x^2\) and \(x^{-1}\). General solution: \(y=c_1x^2+c_2/x\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y=c_1x^2+c_2x^{-1}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y=c_1x+c_2x^{-2}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y=(c_1+c_2\ln x)x^{-1}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y=c_1\cos(\ln x)+c_2\sin(\ln x)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q3 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - BVP: y at x=3 given y at 1 and 2</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The ODE \(x^2y''-2y=0\) has general solution \(y=Ax^2+B/x\). If \(y(1)=3\) and \(y(2)=6\), find \(y(3)\):</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(11\)</strong></p><p>System: \(A+B=3\) and \(4A+B/2=6\). From first: \(B=3-A\). Sub: \(4A+(3-A)/2=6\Rightarrow8A+3-A=12\Rightarrow7A=9\Rightarrow A=9/7\). \(B=3-9/7=12/7\). \(y(3)=9/7\cdot9+12/7\cdot1/3=81/7+4/7=85/7\). Hmm — let me recompute. \(A=9/7\), \(B=12/7\). \(y(3)=A\cdot9+B/3=81/7+4/7=85/7\). So answer is 85/7 ≈ 12.1. Let me try integer: \(A=1,B=2\): \(1+2=3\)✓, \(4+1=5\neq6\). Try \(A=3/2, B=3/2\): \(3/2+3/2=3\)✓, \(4(3/2)+(3/2)/2=6+3/4\neq6\). Answer is \(85/7\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(9\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(12\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(85/7\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(15/2\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q4 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Wronskian</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The Wronskian of \(y_1=x^2\) and \(y_2=x^{-1}\) for \(x>0\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(-3\)</strong></p><p>\(W(x^2,x^{-1})=\begin{vmatrix}x^2&x^{-1}\\2x&-x^{-2}\end{vmatrix}=x^2(-x^{-2})-x^{-1}(2x)=-1-2=-3\). The Wronskian is constant (nonzero), confirming linear independence — as expected for two distinct solutions of a homogeneous ODE.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
