<!-- Q11 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Abel's Theorem</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Abel's theorem: for \(y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y=0\), the Wronskian \(W(y_1,y_2)\) satisfies:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(W(x)=W(x_0)\exp\!\left(-\int_{x_0}^x p(t)\,dt\right)\)</strong></p><p>Abel's identity: \(W'=-p(x)W\), giving \(W(x)=W(x_0)e^{-\int_{x_0}^x p(t)dt}\). Key consequence: \(W\) is either identically zero (if solutions are dependent) or never zero. This is used to classify whether two solutions are linearly independent.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(W=c\,e^{\int p\,dx}\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(W=c\,p(x)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(W(x)=W(x_0)\exp\!\left(-\int_{x_0}^x p(t)\,dt\right)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(W=0\) always]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q12 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - IVP Existence and Uniqueness</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Picard–Lindelöf theorem: the IVP \(y'=f(x,y)\), \(y(x_0)=y_0\) has a unique solution near \(x_0\) if \(f\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) Continuous in \(x\) and Lipschitz in \(y\)</strong></p><p>Picard–Lindelöf: if \(f\) is continuous and Lipschitz in \(y\) (i.e., \(|f(x,y_1)-f(x,y_2)|\leq L|y_1-y_2|\)), then the IVP has a unique local solution. Lipschitz in \(y\) is ensured by \(\partial f/\partial y\) being bounded. Peano's theorem gives only existence (without uniqueness) under just continuity.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Only continuous in \(x\) and \(y\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Continuous in \(x\) and Lipschitz in \(y\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Analytic (real-analytic in \(x\) and \(y\))]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[Bounded everywhere]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q13 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Transform to Constant Coefficients</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The substitution \(t=\ln x\) transforms the Euler–Cauchy equation \(x^2y''+axy'+by=0\) into a linear ODE with:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) Constant coefficients: \(\ddot{y}+(a-1)\dot{y}+by=0\)</strong></p><p>With \(t=\ln x\): \(x\frac{dy}{dx}=\dot{y}\), \(x^2\frac{d^2y}{dx^2}=\ddot{y}-\dot{y}\). Substituting: \((\ddot{y}-\dot{y})+a\dot{y}+by=\ddot{y}+(a-1)\dot{y}+by=0\). This constant-coefficient equation in \(t\) is solved by characteristic equation, then \(t=\ln x\) gives solutions in \(x\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\ddot{y}+(a-1)\dot{y}+by=0\) (constant coefficients)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\ddot{y}+a\dot{y}+by=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(t^2\ddot{y}+at\dot{y}+by=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(\ddot{y}+(a+1)\dot{y}+by=0\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q14 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Green's Function Approach</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>For the BVP \(y''+y=f(x)\), \(y(0)=y(\pi)=0\), the Green's function \(G(x,\xi)\) is used to write:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(y(x)=\int_0^\pi G(x,\xi)f(\xi)\,d\xi\)</strong></p><p>The Green's function \(G(x,\xi)\) encodes the response to a point source: \(y(x)=\int G(x,\xi)f(\xi)d\xi\). For the problem \(-y''=f\) with Dirichlet boundary conditions, \(G(x,\xi)=\begin{cases}x(\pi-\xi)/\pi&x<\xi\\\xi(\pi-x)/\pi&x>\xi\end{cases}\). Green's functions reduce BVPs to integration.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y(x)=\sum_n f_n\phi_n(x)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^\pi G(x,\xi)f(\xi)\,d\xi\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y(x)=G(x,0)f(0)+G(x,\pi)f(\pi)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y(x)=f(x)/G(x,x)\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q15 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Euler Equation Complex Roots</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The Euler–Cauchy equation \(x^2y''+xy'+y=0\) has solution:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (D) \(y=c_1\cos(\ln x)+c_2\sin(\ln x)\)</strong></p><p>Indicial equation: \(m(m-1)+m+1=m^2+1=0\Rightarrow m=\pm i\). Complex roots \(\alpha\pm i\beta\) with \(\alpha=0,\beta=1\). Solution: \(y=x^0(c_1\cos(\ln x)+c_2\sin(\ln x))=c_1\cos(\ln x)+c_2\sin(\ln x)\). This exhibits oscillatory behavior at \(x=0^+\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
