<!-- Q17 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Sturm Comparison</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Sturm's comparison theorem: if \(Q(x)>q(x)\) on \((a,b)\) and \(y''+Qy=0\), \(z''+qz=0\), then between any two zeros of \(z\):</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(y\) has at least one zero (solutions of the "bigger" equation oscillate faster)</strong></p><p>Sturm comparison: if \(Q>q\), then between any two consecutive zeros of \(z\), the solution \(y\) of the equation with larger coefficient has at least one zero. This means solutions oscillate more rapidly when the coefficient is larger. Example: \(y''+y=0\) (zeros at multiples of \(\pi\)) vs \(y''+4y=0\) (zeros at multiples of \(\pi/2\), more frequent).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y\) has at least one zero]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y\) has no zeros]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(y=z\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text><![CDATA[\(|y|>|z|\)]]></text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>
<!-- Q18 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Laplace Transform</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Using Laplace transforms, the solution of \(y''-y=e^t\), \(y(0)=0\), \(y'(0)=0\) has:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(\mathcal{L}\{y\}=\dfrac{1}{(s-1)^2(s+1)}\)</strong></p><p>\(\mathcal{L}\{y''-y\}=\mathcal{L}\{e^t\}\Rightarrow(s^2-1)Y(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}\Rightarrow Y(s)=\frac{1}{(s^2-1)(s-1)}=\frac{1}{(s-1)^2(s+1)}\). Partial fractions then give \(y(t)\). The transform reduces the ODE to algebra.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
