<!-- Q19 --><question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>ODE - Self-Adjoint Form</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>The equation \(y''+p(x)y'+q(x)y=0\) can be written in self-adjoint form \((r(x)y')'+s(x)y=0\) with \(r(x)=\):</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(e^{\int p(x)\,dx}\)</strong></p><p>Multiplying the ODE by the integrating factor \(\mu(x)=e^{\int p\,dx}\): \(e^{\int p}y''+pe^{\int p}y'+qe^{\int p}y=0\Rightarrow(e^{\int p}y')'+qe^{\int p}y=0\). So \(r=e^{\int p}\) and \(s=qe^{\int p}\). This is the Sturm–Liouville form \((ry')'+sy=0\), fundamental to eigenvalue theory.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
